> **DOCUMENT 2 --- COMPANY AGREEMENT (OPERATING AGREEMENT)**

**Provenarc Group LLC --- Co-Equal Member Company Agreement**

This Company Agreement (this \"Agreement\") of Provenarc Group LLC, a
Texas limited liability company (the \"Company\"), is entered into as of
the date last signed below, by and between Dalton Montes and Daniel
Wiglesworth (individually, a \"Member\" and collectively, the
\"Members\"), each holding an equal fifty percent (50%) Membership
Interest. This Agreement sets forth the complete, binding understanding
of the Members with respect to the governance, operation, finances, and
dissolution of the Company and supersedes all prior oral or written
agreements on such matters.

**ARTICLE 1 --- DEFINITIONS**

As used throughout this Agreement, the following terms have the meanings
set forth below. Capitalized terms used but not defined in the body of
this Agreement have the meanings assigned in this Article.

-   \"Agreement\" means this Company Agreement, as amended from time to
    time in accordance with its terms.

-   \"Capital Account\" means the individual account maintained for each
    Member reflecting that Member\'s equity interest in the Company, as
    adjusted pursuant to Article 4.

-   \"Capital Contribution\" means the aggregate amount of cash or fair
    market value of property contributed by a Member to the Company.

-   \"Co-Managing Members\" means Dalton Montes and Daniel Wiglesworth,
    jointly vested with equal management authority over the Company.

-   \"Company\" means Provenarc Group LLC, a Texas limited liability
    company.

-   \"Company Agreement\" has the same meaning as \"Operating
    Agreement\" under the Texas Business Organizations Code.

-   \"Deadlock\" means any situation in which the Co-Managing Members
    are unable to reach agreement on a matter requiring approval after
    exhausting the procedures in Section 5.7.

-   \"Fiscal Year\" means the calendar year, January 1 through December
    31, unless otherwise changed by unanimous written consent.

-   \"IP Assets\" means all intellectual property owned by the Company,
    including trademarks, service marks, trade names, brand elements,
    domain names, software, proprietary methodologies, work product
    templates, client databases, and any registrations or applications
    therefor.

-   \"Majority Vote\" means the affirmative approval of Members holding
    more than fifty percent (50%) of all Membership Interests.

-   \"Member\" means each person listed in Exhibit A and any person
    later admitted in accordance with Article 7.

-   \"Membership Interest\" means the totality of a Member\'s rights and
    obligations in the Company, including economic rights (right to
    share in profits, losses, and distributions) and governance rights
    (right to vote and participate in management), expressed as a
    percentage.

-   \"Net Profits\" and \"Net Losses\" mean the Company\'s taxable
    income or loss for each fiscal year as determined under applicable
    federal income tax principles.

-   \"Subsidiary\" means any entity in which the Company holds a
    controlling or majority ownership interest, including Provenarc Aero
    Solutions and any future subsidiaries formed or acquired by the
    Company.

-   \"Supermajority\" means the affirmative written approval of all
    Members, i.e., one hundred percent (100%) of Membership Interests,
    given the equal 50/50 ownership structure.

-   \"TBOC\" means the Texas Business Organizations Code, as amended
    from time to time.

-   \"Transfer\" means any sale, assignment, pledge, hypothecation,
    gift, bequest, exchange, or other disposition of a Membership
    Interest, whether voluntary or involuntary.

**ARTICLE 2 --- FORMATION AND ORGANIZATION**

**Section 2.1 --- Organization**

The Company has been organized as a Texas limited liability company by
filing a Certificate of Formation with the Texas Secretary of State
pursuant to TBOC § 101.051. The Members adopt this Agreement as the
Company Agreement of the Company and agree to be bound by its terms.

**Section 2.2 --- Principal Office**

The principal office of the Company is located at 100 Park Lane, Suite
11, Kerrville, Texas 78028. This address serves as the Company\'s
official address for all business correspondence, legal filings, and
regulatory notices. The Co-Managing Members may change the principal
office location by mutual written consent, and any such change shall be
reflected promptly in the Company\'s records and in the annual Public
Information Report filed with the Texas Comptroller of Public Accounts.

**Section 2.3 --- Registered Agent**

The Company shall at all times maintain a registered agent in the State
of Texas with a physical street address (not a P.O. Box) as required by
TBOC § 5.201. The registered agent shall be designated and may be
changed by agreement of the Co-Managing Members, with any change filed
with the Texas Secretary of State on Form 401 within a reasonable time.

**Section 2.4 --- Term and Duration**

The Company shall have perpetual existence commencing upon the effective
date of the Certificate of Formation and shall continue unless and until
dissolved pursuant to Article 11 of this Agreement or as required by
applicable law. The resignation, retirement, death, incapacity, or
bankruptcy of a Member shall not automatically cause dissolution of the
Company, which shall continue in existence pursuant to the provisions of
Article 7.

**Section 2.5 --- Purposes and Scope**

The Company\'s primary purposes are: (i) to serve as the parent holding
entity for all Provenarc-branded business ventures; (ii) to own,
protect, manage, license, and enforce the IP Assets across all
Subsidiary operations; (iii) to hold and lease tangible business assets
to Subsidiaries; (iv) to receive distributions and returns from
Subsidiary operations; (v) to form, fund, and oversee Subsidiary
entities; and (vi) to engage in any other lawful business the
Co-Managing Members determine to be in the Company\'s best interest. By
maintaining the Company as the IP and asset holding entity separate from
operations, the Members intend to protect the enterprise\'s core value
from operational liabilities incurred at the subsidiary level.

**Section 2.6 --- Fiduciary Duties**

Each Member and Co-Managing Member owes fiduciary duties to the Company
and to each other Member, including the duty of loyalty and the duty of
care. The duty of loyalty includes the obligation to: (i) account for
and hold as trustee any property, profit, or benefit derived from the
conduct of Company business or from the use of Company property; (ii)
refrain from competing directly with the Company without written consent
of the other Member; and (iii) deal fairly with the Company and the
other Member in all transactions involving the Company.

**ARTICLE 3 --- CAPITAL CONTRIBUTIONS AND ACCOUNTS**

**Section 3.1 --- Initial Capital Contributions**

The initial capital contributions of each Member are set forth in
Exhibit A to this Agreement. Each Member\'s Capital Account shall be
credited with the value of their initial contribution upon execution of
this Agreement.

**Section 3.2 --- Additional Capital Contributions**

No Member shall be required to make any additional capital contribution
to the Company beyond their initial contribution as set forth in Exhibit
A. If the Co-Managing Members unanimously determine that additional
capital is required to fund operations, expand the business, or address
an unforeseen liability, each Member shall have the opportunity, but not
the obligation, to contribute additional capital in proportion to their
Membership Interest. If one Member declines to make an additional
contribution, the contributing Member may, with the consent of the
non-contributing Member, provide additional capital as a loan to the
Company (not as a capital contribution), subject to reasonable written
loan terms.

**Section 3.3 --- Capital Account Maintenance**

The Company shall maintain a separate Capital Account for each Member.
Each Member\'s Capital Account shall be: (i) increased by that Member\'s
Capital Contributions and allocations of Net Profits; (ii) decreased by
that Member\'s distributions received and allocations of Net Losses; and
(iii) adjusted as required to comply with the capital account
maintenance rules under Treasury Regulation § 1.704-1(b). No Member
shall be entitled to interest on any Capital Account balance or capital
contribution unless separately agreed in writing.

**Section 3.4 --- Negative Capital Accounts**

If a Member\'s Capital Account balance becomes negative as a result of
net loss allocations or distributions, such Member shall not be required
to restore such negative balance or make any additional capital
contribution solely on account thereof, except as may be required by
applicable tax law or by specific written agreement.

**Section 3.5 --- Return of Capital**

No Member shall have the right to demand or receive a return of capital
contributions from the Company except upon dissolution and winding up
pursuant to Article 11, or as expressly approved in writing by both
Members. The Company shall not be obligated to return capital
contributions ahead of satisfying Company obligations.

**ARTICLE 4 --- ALLOCATIONS AND DISTRIBUTIONS**

**Section 4.1 --- Allocation of Net Profits**

Net Profits for each fiscal year shall be allocated between the Members
equally --- fifty percent (50%) to Dalton Montes and fifty percent (50%)
to Daniel Wiglesworth --- consistent with their equal Membership
Interests.

**Section 4.2 --- Allocation of Net Losses**

Net Losses for each fiscal year shall be allocated between the Members
equally --- fifty percent (50%) to each Member --- subject to the
limitation that no Member shall be allocated losses in excess of their
positive Capital Account balance plus any amount that Member is
obligated to restore.

**Section 4.3 --- Special Allocations**

Notwithstanding Sections 4.1 and 4.2, the following special allocations
shall be made in the order listed prior to other allocations: (i) any
income or gain required to offset previously made impermissible
distributions; (ii) any qualified income offset to prevent Capital
Account deficits in violation of applicable Treasury Regulations; and
(iii) any other allocations required to ensure this Agreement complies
with applicable federal income tax regulations governing partnership
allocations.

**Section 4.4 --- Timing and Manner of Distributions**

Cash distributions shall be made at such times and in such amounts as
the Co-Managing Members unanimously agree. All distributions shall be
made in equal proportions --- fifty percent (50%) to each Member ---
concurrent with any distribution to the other Member. No distribution
shall be made to one Member without a simultaneous pro-rata distribution
to the other Member.

**Section 4.5 --- Restrictions on Distributions**

No distribution shall be made to any Member if, after giving effect to
such distribution: (i) the Company would be unable to pay its debts as
they become due in the ordinary course; (ii) the fair market value of
the Company\'s total assets would be less than the sum of its total
liabilities; or (iii) the distribution would violate applicable law. The
Co-Managing Members shall be personally liable for any distribution made
in violation of these restrictions.

**Section 4.6 --- Tax Distributions**

To the extent the Company has available distributable cash and without
prejudice to operations, the Co-Managing Members may cause the Company
to make quarterly tax distributions to each Member in amounts estimated
to cover each Member\'s federal and applicable state income tax
liability attributable to their share of the Company\'s taxable income.
Tax distributions shall be made equally to both Members and shall be
treated as advances against future distributions.

**Section 4.7 --- Inter-Company Distributions from Subsidiaries**

Distributions received by the Company from Provenarc Aero Solutions or
any other Subsidiary shall first be applied to: (i) reimbursing the
Company for any documented inter-company loans or advances; (ii)
covering any outstanding Company obligations; and (iii) thereafter
distributed to the Members as provided in this Article 4. The
Co-Managing Members shall document the basis and timing of all
inter-company distributions in the Company\'s books and records.

**ARTICLE 5 --- MANAGEMENT AND OPERATIONS**

**Section 5.1 --- Co-Equal Management Structure**

The Company shall be managed jointly by its two Members acting as
Co-Managing Members. Dalton Montes and Daniel Wiglesworth shall have
equal management authority, equal voting rights, and equal operational
responsibilities. Neither Co-Managing Member shall have unilateral
authority to bind the Company except within the scope of express
authority granted in this Agreement or by separate written resolution.

**Section 5.2 --- Day-to-Day Management Authority**

Each Co-Managing Member, acting individually, shall have authority to
conduct ordinary day-to-day business operations on behalf of the
Company, including: (i) executing contracts and purchase orders up to
Five Thousand Dollars (\$5,000) per transaction; (ii) hiring and
releasing independent contractors; (iii) managing vendor relationships;
(iv) directing Subsidiary operations within authorized budgets; (v)
paying routine operating expenses; (vi) depositing and disbursing
Company funds for authorized purposes; and (vii) executing
non-disclosure agreements and routine service agreements in standard
Company form. Actions within this authority shall not require advance
approval of the other Co-Managing Member but shall be disclosed promptly
in the monthly management report.

**Section 5.3 --- Joint Authority --- Requires Both Signatures**

The following actions require the written consent of both Co-Managing
Members before being undertaken:

-   Entering into any contract with a value exceeding Five Thousand
    Dollars (\$5,000)

-   Hiring any employee (as distinguished from independent contractors)

-   Incurring any debt, line of credit, or financial obligation
    exceeding Ten Thousand Dollars (\$10,000)

-   Making any capital expenditure exceeding Five Thousand Dollars
    (\$5,000)

-   Authorizing any distribution to the Members

-   Entering into any related-party transaction

-   Opening or closing any bank, deposit, or financial account

-   Filing any tax election, amended tax return, or change in accounting
    method

-   Acquiring any asset with a value exceeding Ten Thousand Dollars
    (\$10,000)

-   Commencing, settling, or discontinuing any legal proceeding

-   Granting any lien, mortgage, or security interest in Company assets

-   Entering into any joint venture, partnership, or strategic alliance

-   Executing any agreement that modifies, limits, or transfers IP
    Assets

-   Making any public statement on behalf of the Company regarding
    ownership, finances, or strategy

**Section 5.4 --- Supermajority Actions --- Requires Both Members\'
Written Consent**

The following fundamental actions require the unanimous written consent
of both Members (equivalent to a Supermajority in this 50/50 structure):

-   Amending, restating, or terminating this Company Agreement

-   Admitting any new Member or issuing any additional Membership
    Interest or equity-like instrument

-   Selling, assigning, exclusively licensing, pledging, or otherwise
    encumbering any IP Asset

-   Incurring debt exceeding Twenty-Five Thousand Dollars (\$25,000)

-   Forming, acquiring, merging, dissolving, or selling any Subsidiary

-   Changing the fundamental business purpose of the Company or any
    Subsidiary

-   Converting the Company to a different entity type or merging with
    any other entity

-   Dissolving or winding up the Company

-   Electing tax treatment other than partnership status for federal
    income tax purposes

-   Approving any buy-sell transaction under Article 9

-   Entering into any non-competition, exclusivity, or material
    restriction agreement binding the Company

**Section 5.5 --- Division of Operational Responsibilities**

Without limiting the equal authority of both Co-Managing Members, the
Members may agree by written resolution to designate primary operational
responsibilities between them as follows, subject to revision by mutual
agreement:

  -----------------------------------------------------------------------
  **Dalton Montes --- Primary Focus** **Daniel Wiglesworth --- Primary
                                      Focus**
  ----------------------------------- -----------------------------------
  \[To be determined by mutual        \[To be determined by mutual
  agreement\]                         agreement\]

  Example: Business Development &     Example: Operations & Service
  Partnerships                        Delivery

  Example: Finance & Legal            Example: Technology & Systems
  Coordination                        
  -----------------------------------------------------------------------

Designation of primary responsibilities does not limit either Member\'s
authority within the Joint Authority provisions of Section 5.3. Either
Member may raise any concern regarding operational decisions to the
other Member for resolution.

**Section 5.6 --- Member Compensation and Reimbursement**

Neither Member shall receive any salary, commission, fee, or other
compensation for services rendered to the Company solely in their
capacity as a Member unless separately approved in writing by both
Members. Both Members may be reimbursed promptly for reasonable,
documented out-of-pocket expenses incurred on behalf of the Company,
provided such expenses are consistent with the Company\'s approved
budget or otherwise pre-approved by both Members. Any compensation
arrangement, draw structure, or management fee shall be documented in a
separate written resolution referencing this Agreement.

**Section 5.7 --- Deadlock Resolution**

In the event the Co-Managing Members reach a Deadlock on any matter
requiring joint approval, the following procedures shall be followed in
sequence:

1.  The Members shall first attempt good-faith negotiation for a period
    of thirty (30) days following written notice by either Member that a
    Deadlock exists.

2.  If the Deadlock persists after thirty (30) days, either Member may
    demand non-binding mediation before a mutually agreed mediator with
    experience in Texas business law. Mediation shall be completed
    within sixty (60) days of the demand.

3.  If mediation fails to resolve the Deadlock, the Members shall engage
    an independent Texas business attorney or CPA, mutually selected, to
    provide a written advisory opinion within thirty (30) days.

4.  If the Deadlock continues to prevent necessary Company action for a
    period exceeding one hundred twenty (120) days and involves a matter
    fundamental to Company operations, either Member may invoke the
    buy-sell provisions of Article 9.

**Section 5.8 --- Meetings and Written Consents**

The Members shall hold regular meetings at least semi-annually to review
the Company\'s financial performance, Subsidiary operations, and
strategic direction. Special meetings may be called by either Member
upon seven (7) days\' written notice, or by mutual agreement upon
shorter notice. Meetings may be conducted in person, by telephone, or by
videoconference. Any action required or permitted to be taken at a
meeting may be taken by written consent signed by both Members, without
a meeting, which shall have the same force and effect as a vote at a
duly held meeting. All written consents and meeting minutes shall be
retained in the Company\'s permanent records.

**Section 5.9 --- Annual Business Review**

Not later than sixty (60) days after the close of each fiscal year, the
Co-Managing Members shall conduct an annual business review addressing:
(i) the Company\'s financial performance for the preceding year; (ii)
the performance and status of each Subsidiary; (iii) the IP Assets and
any required registrations, renewals, or enforcement actions; (iv) a
budget and operational plan for the coming year; and (v) any proposed
amendments to this Agreement or to Subsidiary governing documents. The
annual review shall be documented in written meeting minutes retained in
the Company\'s records.

**ARTICLE 6 --- INTELLECTUAL PROPERTY AND ASSET OWNERSHIP**

**Section 6.1 --- Declaration of IP Ownership**

All IP Assets are owned exclusively and irrevocably by Provenarc Group
LLC. No Subsidiary, Member acting in their individual capacity,
employee, independent contractor, or other affiliate shall claim any
ownership right in the IP Assets except pursuant to an express written
license executed by both Co-Managing Members on behalf of the Company.
This structural separation is fundamental to the Company\'s purpose as a
holding entity and shall be strictly maintained at all times.

**Section 6.2 --- Schedule of IP Assets**

The IP Assets include, without limitation, the following:

-   The trade names \"Provenarc Group,\" \"Provenarc Aero Solutions,\"
    and all current and future Provenarc-branded entities or product
    lines

-   All trademarks, service marks, logos, design marks, and brand
    elements associated with any Provenarc entity, whether registered
    with the USPTO or existing as common law marks

-   All internet domain names registered in connection with any
    Provenarc entity, including but not limited to any .com, .aero,
    .net, .org, or country-code domains

-   The RecordVault software platform, including all source code, object
    code, APIs, documentation, user interfaces, and derivative works

-   All proprietary scanning protocols, aviation records digitization
    methodologies, intake procedures, and quality control frameworks

-   All service agreement templates, client onboarding materials,
    pricing models, and work product templates

-   All client databases, prospect lists, partner contact databases, and
    pricing intelligence

-   All marketing materials, website content, photography, video
    content, brochures, and advertising copy developed for any Provenarc
    entity

-   All trade secrets, confidential technical information, and
    non-public business information pertaining to the Company\'s or any
    Subsidiary\'s operations

-   Any inventions, improvements, or discoveries conceived by either
    Member or any contractor in connection with Company business

-   Any future IP developed, acquired, or otherwise coming under the
    Company\'s control

**Section 6.3 --- IP License to Subsidiaries**

The Company shall grant each Subsidiary a license to use the IP Assets
solely within the scope of that Subsidiary\'s authorized operations,
subject to the following terms: (i) the license shall be non-exclusive
and non-transferable; (ii) the license shall be revocable by written
notice from the Company upon Subsidiary dissolution, material breach, or
by unanimous consent of the Co-Managing Members; (iii) the license shall
not permit sublicensing without express written approval; (iv) the
Subsidiary shall use the IP Assets only in the manner prescribed by the
Company and shall not use the Provenarc brand in any way that could
impair the Company\'s trademark rights; and (v) the license may be
royalty-free or royalty-bearing as separately determined by written
inter-company agreement. Any royalty arrangement shall be documented in
the Inter-Company Agreement and shall constitute taxable income to the
Company.

**Section 6.4 --- Work-Made-for-Hire and Assignment Obligation**

All work product, inventions, software, creative works, and other
deliverables created by either Member, any employee, or any contractor
in the course of Company business shall constitute works made for hire
to the maximum extent permitted by law, and all rights therein shall
vest in the Company. To the extent any work does not qualify as a work
made for hire, each Member and contractor shall be deemed to have
assigned all rights, title, and interest therein to the Company
automatically upon creation. Each Member and the Company shall execute
such additional written assignments and instruments as may be required
to perfect and record the Company\'s ownership, including USPTO
assignment filings and copyright registrations.

**Section 6.5 --- Asset Ownership and Titling**

All tangible assets of the enterprise with a value exceeding Two
Thousand Dollars (\$2,000) shall be owned by and titled in the name of
Provenarc Group LLC, regardless of which Subsidiary uses such assets
operationally. Assets shall be made available to Subsidiaries pursuant
to written asset use agreements or equipment lease agreements that are
reflected in both entities\' financial records. Subsidiary financial
statements shall not reflect ownership of IP Assets or any Company
asset. Assets owned by the Company shall be listed in the Asset Schedule
maintained as Exhibit B to this Agreement, which shall be updated
annually.

**Section 6.6 --- Subsidiary Structural Separation --- Piercing
Prevention**

The Co-Managing Members acknowledge that maintaining the structural
separation between the Company and its Subsidiaries is essential to
preserve the limited liability protections afforded by the LLC form.
Accordingly, the Members agree to: (i) maintain separate bank accounts
for each entity; (ii) maintain separate books, records, and financial
statements for each entity; (iii) document all inter-company
transactions by written invoice, agreement, or resolution; (iv) refrain
from commingling funds of the Company with any Subsidiary or personal
funds; (v) conduct each entity\'s business in that entity\'s name; (vi)
cause each entity to hold at least one formal meeting or act by written
consent annually; (vii) not hold out any Subsidiary as the same entity
as the Company; and (viii) maintain adequate capitalization in each
Subsidiary to meet its reasonably anticipated obligations.

**ARTICLE 7 --- MEMBERSHIP INTERESTS AND TRANSFERS**

**Section 7.1 --- Restrictions on Transfer**

No Member may sell, assign, transfer, exchange, pledge, hypothecate, or
otherwise dispose of all or any portion of their Membership Interest,
whether voluntarily or involuntarily, without first complying with the
procedures in this Article 7. Any purported Transfer made in violation
of this Article shall be null and void ab initio and shall not be
recorded in the Company\'s books or be binding on the Company.

**Section 7.2 --- Right of First Refusal on Voluntary Transfer**

If a Member (the \"Offering Member\") desires to Transfer all or any
portion of their Membership Interest to any third party and has received
a bona fide written offer from a prospective transferee, the Offering
Member shall provide written notice to the other Member (the
\"Non-Offering Member\") setting forth the full terms of the proposed
Transfer, including the proposed purchase price, payment terms, and
identity of the proposed transferee. The Non-Offering Member shall have
thirty (30) days from receipt of such notice to elect, by written
notice, to purchase the offered interest on the same terms and
conditions. If the Non-Offering Member does not exercise this right
within thirty (30) days, the Offering Member may complete the Transfer
to the identified third party on terms no more favorable than those
disclosed, provided that such Transfer is completed within ninety (90)
days.

**Section 7.3 --- Admission of Transferee as Member**

No transferee of a Membership Interest shall be admitted as a substitute
Member without the prior written consent of both Co-Managing Members. A
transferee who is not admitted as a Member shall be entitled only to the
economic rights (profits and distributions) associated with the
transferred interest, and shall have no governance, voting, or
management rights. Until admitted, the transferring Member shall remain
liable for all obligations of a Member under this Agreement.

**Section 7.4 --- Permitted Transfers**

Notwithstanding Section 7.1, each Member may Transfer their Membership
Interest without the other Member\'s consent to: (i) a revocable living
trust for estate planning purposes in which the transferring Member is
the sole trustee and primary beneficiary during their lifetime; or (ii)
a wholly owned single-member LLC or corporation that is fully controlled
by the transferring Member, provided that the Member retains full voting
control of such entity at all times. Any such Permitted Transfer shall
not relieve the transferring Member of their obligations under this
Agreement, and any loss of qualifying conditions shall trigger the right
of first refusal under Section 7.2.

**Section 7.5 --- Death or Incapacity**

Upon the death or legal incapacitation of a Member, the personal
representative, executor, or trustee of the deceased or incapacitated
Member\'s estate or trust shall have the rights of an assignee (economic
rights only) but shall not be admitted as a Member. The surviving Member
shall have the right, exercisable within one hundred twenty (120) days
of such event, to purchase the deceased or incapacitated Member\'s
Membership Interest at fair market value, as determined by an
independent certified business appraiser mutually agreed upon by the
parties. If the parties cannot agree on an appraiser within thirty (30)
days, each party shall select one appraiser and the two appraisers shall
select a third, whose determination shall be binding.

**Section 7.6 --- Buy-Sell Provisions (Shotgun Clause)**

Either Member may, at any time after exhausting the Deadlock procedures
in Section 5.7, invoke this buy-sell provision by providing written
notice (the \"Trigger Notice\") to the other Member stating a purchase
price at which the triggering Member is willing either to buy the other
Member\'s entire Membership Interest or sell their own entire Membership
Interest. The receiving Member shall have sixty (60) days from receipt
of the Trigger Notice to elect in writing either to: (i) sell their
Membership Interest to the triggering Member at the stated price; or
(ii) purchase the triggering Member\'s Membership Interest at the same
stated price. Closing shall occur within sixty (60) days of such
election. This provision ensures that either Member may exit the Company
at a fair value and prevents indefinite Deadlock from paralyzing the
business.

**ARTICLE 8 --- BOOKS, RECORDS, AND FINANCIAL REPORTING**

**Section 8.1 --- Books and Records**

The Company shall maintain, at its principal office, complete and
accurate books of account and other Company records, including: (i) a
copy of the Certificate of Formation and all amendments thereto; (ii)
this Agreement and all amendments thereto; (iii) all written consents
and meeting minutes; (iv) all federal and state tax returns for at least
six (6) years; (v) all annual financial statements; (vi) a current list
of all Members and their Membership Interests; (vii) a copy of all
material contracts and agreements; and (viii) all insurance policies.
Each Member shall have access to inspect and copy any of these records
upon not less than five (5) business days\' written notice.

**Section 8.2 --- Fiscal Year and Accounting**

The Company\'s fiscal year shall be the calendar year (January 1 through
December 31). The Company shall use the cash method of accounting for
tax purposes, unless the Co-Managing Members unanimously elect otherwise
or applicable law requires a different method. The Company\'s books
shall be maintained using generally accepted accounting principles
applied consistently.

**Section 8.3 --- Financial Statements and Reporting**

The Co-Managing Members shall cause monthly financial statements (income
statement and balance sheet) to be prepared for the Company and for each
Subsidiary. Quarterly statements shall be reviewed by both Members.
Annual financial statements shall be prepared within sixty (60) days of
fiscal year end. Each Member shall have the right to engage an
independent CPA, at the Member\'s expense, to audit or review the
Company\'s financial records.

**Section 8.4 --- Tax Treatment and Tax Matters**

The Company shall be treated as a partnership for federal and state
income tax purposes unless both Members unanimously elect otherwise. The
Company shall file an annual partnership information return (Form 1065)
and shall provide each Member with a Schedule K-1 no later than March 15
following the end of each fiscal year, or as soon as practicable if an
extension is filed. Neither Member shall make any tax election on behalf
of the Company without the written consent of the other Member. Dalton
Montes and Daniel Wiglesworth shall serve as joint Tax Matters Partners
and shall coordinate the Company\'s tax compliance equally.

**Section 8.5 --- Separate Entity Records**

Separate books, records, and financial statements shall be maintained
for each Subsidiary. No Subsidiary revenues, expenses, assets, or
liabilities shall be reflected in the Company\'s books except through
proper equity accounting and inter-company entries. Inter-company
transactions shall be documented by written agreements, invoices, or
resolutions and shall be entered into on arm\'s-length terms.

**Section 8.6 --- Annual Audit Rights**

Either Member may, upon sixty (60) days\' written notice and no more
than once per fiscal year, require the Company to engage an independent
certified public accountant to conduct a review (not a full audit) of
the Company\'s financial statements. The cost of such review shall be
borne by the Company. A full audit may be required by either Member upon
one hundred twenty (120) days\' written notice, at the requesting
Member\'s expense unless material discrepancies are discovered, in which
case the cost shall be borne by the Company.

**ARTICLE 9 --- EXITING MEMBERS AND DISSOLUTION**

**Section 9.1 --- Voluntary Withdrawal**

No Member may withdraw from the Company prior to dissolution without the
written consent of the other Member. Any attempted withdrawal without
such consent shall be ineffective and shall not relieve the withdrawing
Member of any obligations under this Agreement or applicable law.

**Section 9.2 --- Dissolution Events**

The Company shall be dissolved and its affairs wound up upon the
occurrence of any of the following: (i) unanimous written consent of all
Members to dissolve; (ii) the entry of a decree of judicial dissolution
pursuant to TBOC § 11.303; (iii) the failure to resolve a Deadlock
pursuant to the buy-sell provisions of Section 7.6 within the timeframes
set forth therein; or (iv) any other event that causes dissolution under
applicable Texas law, provided that in each case the remaining
provisions of this Article shall govern the winding up.

**Section 9.3 --- Winding Up**

Upon dissolution, the Co-Managing Members (or a liquidating trustee
appointed by them or by a court) shall wind up the Company\'s affairs
by: (i) completing, terminating, or assigning all pending contracts;
(ii) liquidating assets as appropriate; (iii) paying or making
provisions for all Company debts and obligations; and (iv) distributing
remaining assets to the Members as provided in Section 9.4.

**Section 9.4 --- Priority of Distributions Upon Dissolution**

Upon dissolution, the Company\'s assets shall be applied and distributed
in the following order: (i) first, to creditors of the Company,
including Members in their capacity as creditors, in satisfaction of the
Company\'s debts and obligations; (ii) second, to establish any reserves
for contingent liabilities; and (iii) third, to the Members in
proportion to their positive Capital Account balances after giving
effect to all allocations under Article 4.

**Section 9.5 --- IP Assets Upon Dissolution**

Upon dissolution, the IP Assets shall be valued by an independent
appraiser and shall be: (i) distributed to the Members in equal shares
if both Members desire the IP Assets; (ii) purchased by one Member from
the other at appraised value if only one Member desires them; or (iii)
sold to a third party and the proceeds distributed equally. Neither
Member may transfer IP Assets to a Subsidiary without paying fair market
value consideration to the Company, and no IP Asset distribution shall
be made prior to satisfaction of all Company creditors.

**ARTICLE 10 --- INDEMNIFICATION AND LIABILITY**

**Section 10.1 --- Indemnification of Members and Managing Members**

The Company shall indemnify, defend, and hold harmless each Member and
Co-Managing Member from and against any and all claims, demands, losses,
damages, costs, and expenses (including reasonable attorneys\' fees and
court costs) arising from any act or omission taken by such Member in
good faith on behalf of the Company and within the scope of the
authority granted by this Agreement, to the fullest extent permitted by
TBOC Chapter 101. Indemnification shall not extend to claims arising
from the Member\'s fraud, gross negligence, willful misconduct, breach
of this Agreement, or unauthorized actions.

**Section 10.2 --- Standard of Care**

Each Member, in performing their duties under this Agreement, shall act
in good faith, in a manner reasonably believed to be in the best
interests of the Company, and with the care that a person in a like
position would reasonably exercise under similar circumstances. No
Member shall be liable to the Company or any other Member for any error
of judgment or action taken in good faith, provided such action is not
the result of gross negligence or willful misconduct.

**Section 10.3 --- Insurance**

The Company shall maintain, at minimum, the following insurance
coverages to be reviewed annually by the Co-Managing Members: (i)
general liability insurance; (ii) errors and omissions (professional
liability) insurance; (iii) directors and officers (D&O) liability
insurance; and (iv) such other insurance as the Co-Managing Members deem
appropriate for the Company\'s activities. Insurance shall be obtained
in the Company\'s name and shall name both Co-Managing Members as
additional insureds.

**ARTICLE 11 --- MISCELLANEOUS PROVISIONS**

**Section 11.1 --- Governing Law and Venue**

This Agreement shall be governed by and construed in accordance with the
laws of the State of Texas, without regard to conflict-of-laws
principles. Venue for any legal proceedings shall be Kerr County, Texas.

**Section 11.2 --- Dispute Resolution**

Except for the Deadlock procedures in Section 5.7, any dispute arising
under or related to this Agreement shall be resolved as follows: (i) the
parties shall first attempt in good faith to resolve the dispute by
negotiation for thirty (30) days; (ii) if unresolved, the parties shall
submit the dispute to non-binding mediation before a Texas-licensed
mediator agreed upon by the parties; and (iii) if mediation fails, the
dispute shall be resolved by binding arbitration under the Commercial
Arbitration Rules of the American Arbitration Association, with the
arbitration to be conducted in Kerrville, Texas.

**Section 11.3 --- Confidentiality**

Each Member agrees to maintain strict confidentiality with respect to
all non-public information relating to the Company, its Subsidiaries,
clients, partners, and business strategies. Neither Member shall
disclose such information to any third party without the prior written
consent of the other Member, except as required by law or as necessary
in connection with the performance of their duties under this Agreement.

**Section 11.4 --- Non-Competition**

During the term of this Agreement, neither Member shall, directly or
indirectly, engage in or have an ownership interest in any business that
directly competes with the Company\'s or any Subsidiary\'s core business
activities without the prior written consent of the other Member.
Passive investments not exceeding five percent (5%) of the outstanding
equity of a publicly traded company shall not constitute a violation of
this Section. The non-competition obligation shall survive termination
of membership for a period of two (2) years within a fifty (50) mile
radius of Kerrville, Texas.

**Section 11.5 --- Entire Agreement**

This Agreement, together with all Exhibits and Schedules hereto,
constitutes the entire agreement of the Members with respect to the
subject matter hereof and supersedes all prior negotiations,
representations, warranties, and understandings. No prior or
contemporaneous oral or written statement shall modify or supplement
this Agreement.

**Section 11.6 --- Amendments**

This Agreement may be amended only by a written instrument signed by
both Members. No oral modification shall be effective.

**Section 11.7 --- Severability**

If any provision of this Agreement is found invalid, illegal, or
unenforceable under applicable law, the remaining provisions shall
continue in full force and effect, and such invalid provision shall be
modified to the minimum extent necessary to make it valid and
enforceable.

**Section 11.8 --- Counterparts and Electronic Signatures**

This Agreement may be executed in one or more counterparts, each of
which shall be deemed an original and all of which together shall
constitute one agreement. Electronic signatures transmitted by PDF,
DocuSign, or similar platform shall be deemed valid and binding to the
same extent as original ink signatures.

**Section 11.9 --- Legal Counsel**

Each Member acknowledges that they have had the opportunity to consult
with independent legal counsel of their choosing prior to executing this
Agreement, or have knowingly waived that right. Each Member affirms that
they understand the terms of this Agreement, have entered into it
voluntarily, and have not been subject to any duress, undue influence,
or misrepresentation.

